        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to derive the energy spectrum from spectral line data cube with Velocity Coordinate Spectrum (VCS), the velocity resolution has to be smaller than the sonic speed which is approximately 0.1 kms-1.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>With 1.5" resolution, ALMA can give a spatial resolution down to 3mpc (assuming the distance to be 400pc) which is the predicted size from the turbulent ambipolar diffusion model (mpc). 7" angular scale would be large enough to recover the outermost contour shown in Fig 2. (Scientific case)
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The science goal of this project is to observe HCN(4-3), HCO+(4-3) and H13CN(4-3)

The flux density is approximated with the previous observation from SMA HCN(3-2) (3.7" x 3.4"; 8.3Jy(beam kms-1)-1 ) and the intensity ratio between (4-3)/(3-2)transition ~1/5 obtained from RADEX. With the proposed ALMA beam (1.5"), we expect the line intensity from HCN(4-3) to be 29.6 mJy (ALMA beam 0.1kms-1)-1. Since HCO+ transition is usually shown brighter than HCN transition, for our purpose, HCN sets the lower limit for our S/N ratio estimation. 

With S/N = 9.9 at the flux peak, it would be able to resolve the structure (Fig 2. in Scientific case) up to 7.5" with approximate S/N ~ 3 arcoss the velocity channel.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
