    <prp:abstract>Protostellar discs are widely observed, but simply angular momentum conservation cannot explain their formation. This is because the typical angular momentum is not enough to overcome the observed magnetic tension, i.e. the so-called magnetic braking catastrophe; however, the braking efficiency depends on how well magnetic fields can couple with gas. Based on the MHD induction equation, good coupling (flux freezing) is a reasonable approximation only at large scales (e.g. cloud scale). At small scales (decoupling scale L), turbulent ambipolar diffusion (TAD, the decoupling of turbulence from magnetic fields) is likely to play a role. If L is comparable with the disc-formation scale, TAD will help to release the magnetic brake. With unprecedented sensitivity, ALMA offers the first opportunity to directly probe L, a critical parameter to understanding disc formations.</prp:abstract>
